>[Question]
>Dear Dr. Math,
>I am beginning to look at the mathematical software Mathematica, and 
>am looking at a list of lists.  I need to extract an element from the 
>larger list, which is a smaller list of the form {a,b,c,d,e}.  From 
>here, I need to assign values to the elements in the smaller list, 
>and then evaluate an expression.  I need to do this for 
>all "sublists" in the larger list.  My first roadblock is trying to 
>assign values to the elements in a given sublist.  In whatever way I 
>try to do this, the entire sublist is redefined as an entirely new 
>list, rather than assigning its elements values.  See below for an 
>example.  Can you help? Thanks!
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>Permutations[{a,b,c}][[2]]  
>
>((this gives the list {a,c,b}))
>
>Permutations[{a,b,c}][[2]]={1,2,4}
>
>((this should give a value 1, c value 2, and b value 4, but it does 
>not))
>
>a^2+b-c
>
>((ideally this gives 1^2+4-2, or 3, but it does not))
>

Hi Genny,

Thanks for writing to Dr Math.  You're right, but

  {a, b, c} = Permutations[{1, 2, 4}][[2]]

works.

If you have any questions about this or need more help, please write
back and show me what you have been able to do, and I will try to
offer further suggestions.

- Doctor Vogler, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

